page.title: 02LANDSCAPE NEAR SEISDON
page.content: This is a flattish area with few physical features. In the north there is a small conifer-covered hill named,rather surprisingly "Alder Coppice". The southern part of the block includes some of a narrow ridge called "Abbot's Castle Hill" which although not very high is the most prominent feature of the district and provides a very good vantage point. Levels in the area vary between eighty and one hundred and forty metres above sea level. There is practically no visible water. No river or broad stream flows through the area and there are no lakes, resevoirs or canals. One small pond in the south-west corner is the only noticeable stretch of water.
